With these challenges in mind, it is difficult to convey the thought that failure to provide rather more general education (10-years required by directive 2005/36/EC, or 12-years as recommended by the WHO
9
) has profound implications not just for the professions concerned, but also for their societies. Without data to support this, it has been pointed out time and time again that the gender of the university is predominantly male. This is therefore a question of human rights. Women seem to be signally disadvantaged by this. With that go all the assumptions about family life, the health of the family and community, and the modelling of education and professional opportunities for future generations. It is easy to conclude that this is a vicious cycle in need of being broken. For many nurses and midwives in central Europe, that is exactly what the implementation of this directive represents. It is therefore not just a way of changing the nature of the profession for the good of society. It is also a way of achieving better education and development for a disadvantaged half of the population. This is major change in what are often still, from a western European perspective, unthinkingly chauvinistic societies. It is not deliberate; it is simply unawareness and is why the negotiation of the implementation of this directive is so complex and difficult. It demands a change of attitude in a field of understanding where many people, men and women, had not previously thought about the implications of what was currently going on.
